    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wireless in Finland</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alex Friedlander letter says prevalence of wireless communications in Finland is in part due to high cost of conventional telephone service (July 13 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Wireless Valhalla: Hints of the Cellular Future'' (July 13), on the prevalence of wireless communications technology in Finland and Scandinavia, confirmed what we saw on a recent visit to Finland. One reason for the popularity of mobile telephones in Scandinavia is the high  cost of conventional telephone service. The cost for both telephone installation and the per-call rates (both local and long distance) for a Finnish household is substantially higher than here in the United States, as is the cost of using pay telephones.</p>
        <p>ALEX FRIEDLANDER  Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
